When you define a variable inside an `if` block, it&#39;s scope is limited to that block of code, and it&#39;s effectively gone when that block of code ends.

To avoid this specific error, you can change your code to:

    public static int KiminMaaşıDahaFazla(object o1, object o2)
    {
        // We need to define k1 and k2 outside of the if block 
        // in order to use them outside of the if block
        MaviYaka k1 = null;
        BeyazYaka k2 = null;

        if (true)
        {
            k1 = (MaviYaka) o1;
        }
        else { }
        if (true)
        {
            k2 = (BeyazYaka) o2;
        }
        else { }

        if (k1.maaş &gt; k2.maaş) { return 1; }
        else { return 2;}
    }

Also, there is no point in using `if (true) { // do something } else {}`, though I assume that&#39;s there for some testing purposes, but your whole method can be simplified to one line:

    public static int KiminMaaşıDahaFazla(object o1, object o2)
    {
        return ((MaviYaka)o1).maaş &gt; ((BeyazYaka)o2).maaş ? 1 : 2;
    }

----

A better way to do this might be to simply check the type of `o1` and `o2` at runtime, and get the property values from the objects that way instead.

For example:

    public static int KiminMaaşıDahaFazla(object o1, object o2)
    {
        // I&#39;ve assumed the type is &#39;int&#39;; change to the correct type if needed
        int k1_maaş = 0;
        int k2_maaş = 0;

        // Check the type of object and assign our variables as appropriate
        if (o1 is MaviYaka) k1_maaş = ((MaviYaka) o1).maaş;
        else if (o1 is BeyazYaka) k1_maaş = ((BeyazYaka) o1).maaş;

        if (o2 is MaviYaka) k1_maaş = ((MaviYaka) o2).maaş;
        else if (o2 is BeyazYaka) k1_maaş = ((BeyazYaka) o2).maaş;

        return k1_maaş &gt; k2_maaş ? 1 : 2;
    }

---

Another option is to create an interface that has the common properties between the two classes, implement the interface on both classes, and then have this method take in two arguments of the interface type:

For example:

    public interface ICommonYaka
    {
        int maaş { get; set; }
    }
    public class MaviYaka : ICommonYaka
    {
        public int maaş { get; set; }
    }
    public class BeyazYaka : ICommonYaka
    {
        public int maaş { get; set; }
